04458nam a22005175i 9780773569256DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735692567 a10.1515/97807735692562doi  a(DE-B1597)657672  a(OCoLC)76898606  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aB1409.C344 ǂb S836 2001eb 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a230/.5233/0921 aSuderman, Jeffrey M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrthodoxy and Enlightenment :bGeorge Campbell in the Eighteenth Century /cJeffrey M. Suderman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (312 p.) :bIllustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v3200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations Used in the Notes -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tGeorge Campbell: Life and Works -- tThe Making of a Christian Philosopher (to 1771) -- tThe Years of Achievement (1771–1790) -- tThe Height of Reputation (from 1790) -- tNatural Knowledge: The Enlightened Campbell -- tPhilosophy in Theory -- tPhilosophy in Practice -- tThe Limits of Enlightenment -- tRevealed Knowledge: The Religious Campbell -- tCampbell’s Theology -- tReligious Problems and Controversies -- tThe Limits of Moderatism -- tConclusion -- tAppendices -- tSchedule of Divinity Lectures Given by George Campbell and Alexander Gerard during the 1786–87 Term -- tCampbell’s Creed -- tA Checklist of Campbell’s Correspondence -- tGeorge Campbell in the Eighteenth Century: A Bibliographical Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGeorge Campbell (1719-1796) has long been regarded as a seminal figure in the development of modern theories of persuasion, but modern students of rhetoric seldom look beyond his Philosophy of Rhetoric to his equally important religious writings. Campbell is portrayed as a secular figure, and his contributions to eighteenth-century Christian apology have been largely forgotten. In his own time, however, Campbell had an international reputation as a champion of the Gospel miracles against the sceptical assaults of the philosopher David Hume and as a respected biblical scholar and authority on Church history. Orthodoxy and Enlightenment is the first study to deal with the entire range of Campbell's interests and publications. Suderman sets Campbell firmly in his eighteenth-century context, reconstructing his life and times from contemporary and manuscript sources. He argues that while Campbell's wide-ranging scholarly and scientific interests made him as much a man of the Enlightenment as his better-known contemporaries Voltaire and Hume, he used the critical tools of the Enlightenment to defend a sincere and orthodox Christian faith. The detailed reconstruction of Campbell's apologetic system will be of interest to students of history, philosophy, literary criticism, rhetoric, and religious thought, as well as to general readers interested in the eighteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356925640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773569256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773569256/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles